#. Tag: title
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1185
#, no-c-format
msgid "Levenberg–Marquardt Solver"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1187
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Levenberg-Marquardt (LM) algorithm is used to solve non-linear least squares problems. The GNU Science Library provides an implementation of the solver. These resources provide more details:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1205
#, no-c-format
msgid "The Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm is a new feature added for the Linear 1 Pass focus algorithm. It is a non-linear least-squares solver and thus suitable for many different equations. The basic idea is to adjust the equation y = f(x,P) so that the computed y values are as close as possible to the y values of the datapoints provided, so that the resultant curve fits the data as best as it can. P is a set of parameters that are varied by the solver in order to find the best fit. The solver measures how far away the curve is at each data point, squares the result and adds them all up. This is the number to be minimized, lets call is S. The solver is supplied with an initial guess for the parameters, P. It calculates S, makes an adjustment to P and calculates a new S1. Provided S1 &lt; S then we are moving in the right direction. It iterates through the procedure until:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1221
#, no-c-format
msgid "the delta in S is less than a supplied limit (convergence has been reached), or"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1226
#, no-c-format
msgid "the maximum number of iterations has been reached, or"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1230
#, no-c-format
msgid "the solver encountered an error."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1234
#, no-c-format
msgid "The solver is capable of solving either an unweighted or weighted set of datapoints. In essence, an unweighted set of data gives equal weight to each datapoint when trying to fit a curve. An alternative is to weight each datapoint with a measure that corresponds to how accurate the measurement of the datapoint actually is. In our case this is the variance of star HFRs associated with the datapoint. The variance is the standard deviation squared."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#. +> trunk5
#: ekos-focus.docbook:1242
#, no-c-format
msgid "Currently the solver is used to fit either a parabolic or a hyperbolic curve."
msgstr ""

